LAST UPDATES

Munich Center for Machine Learning to be permanent

The Munich Center for Machine Learning (MCML), a joint initiative of LMU and TUM, has been granted funding as a permanent establishment following a positive evaluation. MCML was founded in 2018 as one of six AI centers of excellence throughout Germany and has been funded by the German Federal Ministry of Education and Research since then. The MCML is set to receive 19.6 million euros every year.

Read the full article here

The LRZ turns 60

The Leibniz Supercomputing Center celebrated its 60th anniversary in a large celebration ceremony including the Bavarian State Minister for Science and Art Markus Blume and the President of the Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities Prof. Dr. Thomas O. Höllmann, among many other guests.

Read more here

AI in management: “AI can make predictions but not decisions”

Prof. Dr. Stefan Feuerriegel is the head of the new Institute of Artificial Intelligence in Management at LMU Munich School of Management since August 2021. In this interview he talks about his newest paper "Bringing Artificial Intelligence to Business Management" in Nature Machine Intelligence on how managers and businesses can (and already do) use AI.

Read the full article here

Between AI and art

Prof. Dr. Björn Ommer, holder of the newly established Chair of AI for Computer Vision and Digital Humanities/the Arts at LMU, explains his work at the intersection between the Faculty of History and the Arts and the Faculty of Mathematics, Informatics and Statistics.

Read the full article here
UPCOMING EVENTS

New Munich AI Lectures

The Munich AI Lectures series organized by the Munich Center for Machine Learning, ELLIS Munich, the Munich Data Science Institute at TUM, and the Center for Advanced Studies at LMU. has announced three new speakers: Prof. Dr. Stéphane Mallat from the Collège de France on September 7, Prof. Dr. Max Welling from the University of Amsterdam on October 5 and Prof. Dr. Michael Bronstein from the University of Oxford and Twitter on November 2.

More details to be announced here

This newsletter will take a brief summer break next month. We will be back with all the news on October 1 in time for the new semester.
